There are three aspects of Christianity. First, and famously, it is the bitter attack on Christianity, especially its effects on modernity. Christianity is responsible for breeding (or domesticating) human beings into a herd animal; Christianity espouses hatred of rationality, but also the body and any bodily desire for happiness (e.g. lust). Second, the same Buddhist concept of need is at the root of the ‘love of man for God’. Third, the same themes of desire and redemption as the use of the metaphor of blood are fundamental in many accounts of philosophy. The symbol of blood, thus, becomes the concept of both the infrequent recurrence of two contrasting (but distinct) traditions.

